  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Notifying authorities about potential illegal activities\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n4. Record keeping\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n- Preserving customer identification documents\n- Ensuring records are available for potential investigations\n\n5. Risk assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers and transaction types\n- Implementing enhanced due diligence for higher-risk scenarios\n\n6. International regulations\n- Complying with global standards like FATF recommendations\n- Following jurisdiction-specific legal requirements\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant financial penalties, legal consequences, and potential loss of operating licenses.\n\nThese obligations aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the integrity of the global financial system.",
